Welcome!

Today we are working on loess models and predictions, and trying to reinforce some foundational concepts in machine learning. In doing so, we will discuss how R generates random numbers, create a test-train split, and see how changing the span of a loess model affects its performance.

# Setup your workspace

Let's start with loading the required packages and our data. We don't want to include this in the PDF, so we add `include = FALSE` to the chunk header.

```{r setup, include = FALSE}
# load up our trusty friend, tidyverse
library(tidyverse)
library(skimr)
library(gridExtra) # you may need to install this with install.packages()
library(modelr) # you also may need to install this

# load school-level data from the TN Star experiment
STAR_School <- read_csv(file = "STAR_K-3_Schools.csv")

theme_set(theme_bw()) # set a plot theme for the entire doc

```

# Exploring the data

We will explore the relationship between two school-level variables using both a familiar *parametric* approach (linear regression) and our newfound non-parametric friend loess. We will be investigating the relationship between the proportion of Kindergartners receiving free lunch (`gkfrlnch`) and the proportion of kindergartners that are White (`gkwhite`). First we'll get started by just examining a scatter plot and the distributions of the data.

```{r data_explore}
