# Making a test-train split

Before we move on, let's make a test-train split of our data. There are many ways to do this. One way is to randomly separate to our data into two parts. We'll need some random numbers for this, so before we dive in, let's also briefly discuss how random numbers and sampling in R work.

```{r seed_sample}
# set a seed to the random number generator as your birthday or a favorite number
set.seed(12341234)

# as a demonstration of how seeds and samples work, we will each sample and see 
# what the mean and distribution is for the class
sample(STAR_School$gkfrlnch, size = 1) # group activity, what do you get from here?

```

OK, now for the fun part. We will take our STAR school sample and divide it into two samples, a **training** dataset and a **testing** dataset. Dividing our data into two groups allows us to create a model using the training data, and evaluate how well it performs by applying it to the testing data.

Split can be 50/50, 30/70, 10/90, depends on the size of your dataset

```{r test_train, warning=FALSE}
train_ids <- sample(STAR_School$schid, 
                    size = length(STAR_School$schid) / 2, 
                    # we want the sample to be half the size
                    replace = FALSE) # we do not want to draw the same ID twice

# filter the full dataset to get the training and test splits
STAR_train <- STAR_School %>%
  filter(schid %in% train_ids)

nrow(STAR_train) # half of the data

STAR_test <- STAR_School %>%
  filter(!schid %in% train_ids) 
# the "!" negates the statement and provides the opposite result 

nrow(STAR_test)

# check out the results of our Training and Test Data by looking at scatters
p2 <- ggplot(STAR_train, aes(x = gkwhite, y = gkfrlnch)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Percent of White Kindergarten students",
       y = "Percent of Kindergarten students on\nFree or Reduced Price Lunch", 
       title = "Training data")

p3 <- ggplot(STAR_test, aes(x = gkwhite, y = gkfrlnch)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Percent of White Kindergarten students",
       y = "Percent of Kindergarten students on\nFree or Reduced Price Lunch",
       title = "Testing data")

grid.arrange(p2, p3, ncol = 2)

```

**Concept question:** Do the two datasets differ in any notable way?  How do they differ, if so?

# Fitting Loess models

Now we will use our training data to fit a series of loess models using different spans and create predictions. We will also fit a linear model. Recall that when we move from parametric models to non-parametric models (like loess) we trade simplicity and interpretability of a model for greater flexibility and more accurate predictions.

To examine how these look, we will also plot the results, and evaluate each model by calculating the RMSE on (at first) just the *training* data. As a reminder, the RMSE which tells us "how wrong" on average a prediction is for a given dataset. This is a critical concept in data science, so it is important to develop a good understanding of what it means.

```{r train_loess_model, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
# set some span variables for us to test
span_m1 <- .5
span_m2 <- .8
span_m3 <- 1.4

# create Loess models for the spans we set and also a linear model
m1 <- loess(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = STAR_train, span = span_m1)
m2 <- loess(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = STAR_train, span = span_m2)
m3 <- loess(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = STAR_train, span = span_m3)
mlm <- lm(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = STAR_train)

# plot the three loess predictions
STAR_train %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = gkfrlnch, x = gkwhite)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(span = span_m1, method = "loess", se = FALSE, aes(color = "Span 0.5")) + 
  geom_smooth(span = span_m2, method = "loess", se = FALSE, aes(color = "Span 0.8"))  +
 geom_smooth(span = span_m3, method = "loess", se = FALSE, aes(color = "Span 1.4")) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(color = "Linear model"), method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "darkgreen", "orange"),
                     name = "Model")

STAR_train <- STAR_train %>%
  mutate(pred_m1 = predict(m1),
         pred_m2 = predict(m2),
         pred_m3 = predict(m3),
         pred_mlm = predict(mlm))

# get the error for each observation
STAR_train <- STAR_train %>%
  mutate(error_m1 = gkfrlnch - pred_m1,
         error_m2 = gkfrlnch - pred_m2,
         error_m3 = gkfrlnch - pred_m3,
         error_mlm = gkfrlnch - pred_mlm)

# calculate the RMSE for each model
m1_rmse_train <- sqrt(mean(STAR_train$error_m1^2))
m2_rmse_train <- sqrt(mean(STAR_train$error_m2^2))
m3_rmse_train <- sqrt(mean(STAR_train$error_m3^2))
mlm_rmse_train <- sqrt(mean(STAR_train$error_mlm^2))

# compare train RMSE
train_rmse <- tibble(span = c( span_m1, span_m2, span_m3, "linear" ),
                    train_rmse = c( m1_rmse_train, m2_rmse_train, 
                                    m3_rmse_train, mlm_rmse_train)
                   )

knitr::kable(train_rmse, digits = 2)

```

