Side note: `modelr` (introduced more in [this chapter of the online textbook](https://lmiratrix.github.io/S022/Prediction_and_Visualization_with_Models.html)) provides a neat way to generate predictions and residuals for all of our multiple models:

```{r modelr}
# predictions from each model for each observation
# make sure to remove "pred" and "error" columns here first
STAR_train_mdlr <- STAR_train %>%
  select(-starts_with("pred"), 
  -starts_with("error"))
STAR_train_mdlr1 <- STAR_train_mdlr %>% 
  gather_predictions(m1, m2, m3, mlm)

STAR_train_mdlr2 <- STAR_train_mdlr %>% 
  gather_residuals(m1, m2, m3, mlm) %>%
  select(schid, model, resid) # only need schid, model, and residuals columns

# we can then pivot both of these dataframes wider since we have
# rows for each model, and join them together again for easy ggplotting !
STAR_train_mdlr1 <- STAR_train_mdlr1 %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = model, values_from = pred,
              names_prefix = "pred_")

STAR_train_mdlr2 <- STAR_train_mdlr2 %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = model, values_from = resid,
               names_prefix = "error_")

STAR_train_mdlr <- left_join(STAR_train_mdlr1, STAR_train_mdlr2, by = "schid")

STAR_train_mdlr
  
```

## More info on Loess regression

Loess fits a polynomial equation within a sliding window of the data - the span determines how "large" this window is. More precisely, when the span is less than 1, it represents the proportion of the data that are considered to be neighbors of *x*. Neighboring points are weighted using a tricubic function: $(1 - (dist/maxdist)^3)^3$, where $maxdist$ is the maximum observed distance for the $p$ explanatory variables specified. When span is larger than 1, all points are used and the maximum distance is set to be $span^{1/p}$ times the maximum distance.

A very large span will approximate a quadratic function:

```{r large span, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
span_large <- 1e6

m1_span_large <- loess(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = STAR_train, span = span_large)

STAR_train %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = gkfrlnch, x = gkwhite)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(span = span_large, method = "loess", se = FALSE, 
              aes(color = "Large span"),
              linewidth = 2) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(color = "Quadratic model"), 
              method = "lm", formula = y ~ x + I(x^2), se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue"),
                     name = "Model")

```

# Evaluating the models by using the "test" split

We've now run 3 loess models and calculated the RMSE of each in order to evaluate how they perform **on the data with which they were trained**. An important limitation is that smaller spans will *always* have lower RMSE for the data that they were trained on. Using the RMSE of the data that it was trained on is dangerous, because it causes you to choose over-fit models.

Now we will see how the models perform on the the "test" data which we haven't touched. Again, we will get the predictions for each model on the _new data_ (**without refitting the models**) and calculate the RMSE for each using the `STAR_test` data.

