# Extension 1: finding the optimal span (this is cool, so you should try it):

Using the above steps, we saw how to find the model with the lowest RMSE on the test data. But we only tested 3 spans. So how do we find the best-fitting model when we want to test a lot of spans? That is what we will do now. We will do this by creating a function and then using that function a bunch of times with `map`.

```{r extension 1}

# create a function that takes a span and returns the RMSE on the test data 
# after fitting a loess on the training data with the given span 

get_rmse <- function(span = 0.5) {
  
  test <- STAR_test
  train <- STAR_train
  
  # fit the model with the given span on the TRAINING data
  model <- loess(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite, data = train, span = span)

  # get the predictions with the model on the TESTING data
  test$predictions <- predict(model, newdata = test)
  train$predictions <- predict(model)

  # calculate the error for each observation in the test data
  rmse_test <- sqrt(mean((test$predictions - test$gkfrlnch)^2))
  rmse_train <- sqrt(mean((train$predictions - train$gkfrlnch)^2))
  rmse_list = tibble(span = span,
                     test_rmse = rmse_test, 
                     train_rmse = rmse_train)
  
  return(rmse_list)
}

# test to make sure it matches
get_rmse(0.5) 

# now we will create a vector of spans to try 
spans <- seq(from = 0.5, to = 2, by = .05)

# run the function on each value of the spans vector
rmse <- map_dfr(spans, get_rmse) # run the function on each of the spans

# get the best span to minimize RMSE
best.span <- rmse %>% 
  slice_min(test_rmse) %>% 
  pull(span)

best.span

# indicate whether spans result in under or overfit models
rmse <- rmse %>%
  mutate(span.fit = ifelse(span == best.span, "Best",
                           ifelse(span > best.span, "Underfit", "Overfit")))

# plot the rmses and spans
p5 <- rmse %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = span, y = test_rmse)) +
  geom_line( color = "grey" ) +
  geom_point( aes(color = span.fit) ) +
  labs(x = "Span", y = "RMSE", color = "Quality of span",
       title = "Span performance on Testing data RMSE")

p5

# compare train and test rmse
rmsesL <- pivot_longer(rmse, cols = c(train_rmse, test_rmse), 
                       names_to = "dataset",
                       values_to = "rmse")

p6 <- rmsesL %>% 
  ggplot(aes( span, rmse, col = dataset) ) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(x = "Span", y = "RMSE", color = "Dataset",
         title = "Comparing span performance on training vs. test data RMSE") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue"),
                     labels = c("Test RMSE", "Train RMSE"))

p6
```

# Extension 2: Using our model to predict outcomes in fake data

With prediction models, we can extend our models to predict outcomes in new data with fake covariates, and then plot our results for interpretation purposes. This is discussed more in [this chapter](https://lmiratrix.github.io/S022/Prediction_and_Visualization_with_Models.html). Feel free to come back to this or the handouts to use as a reference!

This example does not use loess, but instead fits a new linear model to our full `STAR_school` dataset. First load up `modelr`, which we'll be using to generate the fake covariate data.

```{r extension 2a}

# A new, more saturated linear model
extension_model <- lm(gkfrlnch ~ gkwhite * schlurbn, data = STAR_School)
# note: this introduces `schlurbn` (categorical variable for school urbanicity) 
# and an interaction term between `schlurbn` and `gkwhite`

texreg::screenreg(extension_model) # let's view these results


```

Now, use `modelr` to make all combinations between `gkwhite` and the categories of school urbanicity.

```{r extension 2b}

fake_data <- STAR_School %>% data_grid(gkwhite, schlurbn)

# data_grid calls on tidyr's `expand` function
# the default here uses the unique values of gkwhite 
# present in the original data

# how many rows of fake_data do we end up with?
fake_data

# how many would we have ended up with if we did: 
  data_grid(gkwhite = 1:100, schlurbn)

```

Now let's generate predictions for our fake data using our new model and plot these predictions.

```{r extension 2c, warning=FALSE, message=FALSE}
# you can use modelr directly to add predictions to the fake data
fake_data <- fake_data %>% add_predictions(extension_model)

ggplot(fake_data, aes(x = gkwhite, y = pred)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~schlurbn) +
  labs(y = "Percent of Kindergarten students on\nFree or Reduced Price Lunch",
       x = "Percent of White Kindergarten students")

ggplot(fake_data, aes(x = gkwhite, y = pred)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~schlurbn) +
  geom_point(data = STAR_School, aes(y = gkfrlnch), alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(y = "Percent of Kindergarten students on\nFree or Reduced Price Lunch",
       x = "Percent of White Kindergarten students")

```

Anything you notice here when we plot our original data over these slopes? Note: If we wanted to compare different models, we could also use the handy `gather_predictions` function to generate predictions from each of these models for our fake data.
